Barack Obama receives the Nobel Peace Prize as fourth US president
American President Barack Obama comes to Oslo, Norway, for 26 hours to receive the Nobel Peace Prize here as the fourth US President in history.
He also receives the diploma, the medal and a cheque of $1.4 million for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among peoples.
The head of the White House arrives tomorrow together with his wife Michelle in the northwegian metropolis and will be busy all the time.
First of all, he visits the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time with the five committee members who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organisations.
The presidential couple then planned a meeting with the Norwegian king Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit culminates with the ceremony at which Obama takes over the prestigious prize.
He receives this as the fourth US president, but only as the third who accepts the prize directly in office.
The White House already envisaged Obama speaking about the war in Afghanistan when he took over the prize.
The President does not want to evade this issue because he knows that he is taking over the prize as a President who is currently waging war in two countries.
He strengthened the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forgets to highlight.
At the ceremony Obama also received the gold medal, diploma and cheque of ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate the money for charitable purposes, but he has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The event programme will then include a banquet with the President and his wife, where the Prime Minister and another 250 invited guests will be present in addition to Norway ’ s King and Queen.
Obama was very reluctant to face the price from the outset.
He stated, for example, that he had the feeling that he did not deserve the price entirely.
He repeated several times that it is not only for him, but for those who aspire to the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that this is for him "an invitation to act".
