Vaccination against pneumococci free and voluntary
Immunization against pneumococci will change the habitat from January.
It is said to be the first for families free and voluntary.
But voices are already saying that the obligation to vaccinate would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of free vaccination against pneumococci culminate.
The pharmaceutical institute already determines the maximum prices of vaccines that health insurance companies have to pay.
The experts are also aware of the vaccination process.
New vaccination
Vaccines free for August and children
From January onwards, children can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococci, which were born on 2 August last year and later.
The condition is that they have not yet received a vaccination dose.
Those who have already started vaccination in the last year or earlier must also pay for repeat vaccination themselves.
The first dose of vaccination must be given between the 3 and 5 months of the child's life.
Last year, a quarter of the families had their children vaccinated against pneumococci.
The parents paid 1600 crowns and more for a dose.
The vaccination of the youngest children requires four doses.
On the whole, the experts estimate that health insurance companies spend 300,000 to 450,000 crowns per year on vaccination doses.
But they save on the treatment that children would need without vaccination.
Until now, the state has spent about 500,000 per year on all land vaccinations for children.
The obligation to vaccinate was introduced with the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococci cause middle ear inflammation, but also serious infections including cerebral inflammation and blood poisoning.
Pneumococcal infections lead to the death of up to 28 children up to 10 years of age in hospitals per year.
Outside the Czech Republic, the obligation to vaccinate children against pneumococci was introduced in about 40 countries.
Will vaccination be a duty?
At the same time, it is said that this vaccination could be a duty in the future.
From January onwards, the insurance will be paid and voluntary.
Rudolf Kalovsky, head of the Nahlas Civil Association, mentioned that the obligation to vaccinate would be better.
His association is already promoting pneumococci vaccination in the long term.
The experts at the international conference in which our association was involved were not very satisfied with the fact that we have voluntary vaccination.
This is not quite ideal.
On the other hand, we are glad that we have succeeded in enforcing at least that.
I believe that this is the way we have to go now, Kalovsky said.
However, the Ministry of Health does not want to change the vaccination procedure against pneumococci.
At this moment we do not consider this at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sesen.
Voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages, doctors claim.
Hana Cabrnochova, president of the Association of Practical Pediatricians, admits that voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages.
If all children were vaccinated, one could think about reducing the number of repetitive vaccines "In a situation where the vaccine is so expensive, we understand the political decision that this vaccination has been started as a voluntary one", says all dingst Cabrnochova.
Experts expect more than 80 percent of parents to vaccinate their infants against pneumococci from next year.
Vaccination against pneumococci is also groundbreaking in the fact that it is the first area vaccination that is paid by health insurance and not by the state.
Insurance companies should spend the money on prevention to save them for further treatment, Cabrnochova says.
Doctors have to buy the vaccines themselves.
This, however, involves a concern of the practical paediatricians concerning the purchase of vaccines.
According to the original project, the vaccines should be purchased by insurance companies and the doctors should receive them on the same path as other vaccines issued to them by the state.
However, some MEPs feared that the insurance companies could 'export the money from the health insurance company'.
Therefore, doctors will have to buy the vaccines themselves and wait until the insurance companies pay them.
According to estimates, individual practical doctors will have to invest 40,000 crowns per month, which is a significant sum.
This will not be easy, says Cabrnochova.
