Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters voted in favour of a construction ban for minarets and the concern about the alleged Islamization of Europe is widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, has written a well-founded and well-considered report on whether Muslims can be integrated - and integrated into one of the most explicitly secularized societies in Europe.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's last work: "Why the French don't love headscarves" (2006), an elegant and densely arguing study of a dispute that divided and occupied the country for more than a decade and whose effects are still perceptible today.
Bowen ’ s latest book offers a more comprehensive and bold spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he not only wants to know what politicians and the media are saying about Islam in France, but what is really happening in the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now offer the 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls them "Islamic freedom".
He is a good listener, he gives back debates between teachers and students about the questions they are most concerned about.
Should a Muslim marry in a mosque or town hall (or both)?
Should young Muslims be taught about the evolution and rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use a interest-oriented banking system to get a mortgage?
They are these seemingly profane matters, he claims, which make up daily life, quite contrary to the political dramas that occupy the media.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them with a well-known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, an Arabic Muslim scholar and academician born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open the debate on how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen in a modern secular society on the other.
They do not have all the arguments on their side.
Conservatives are suspicious of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists who questioned Bowen are usually divided against their Salafi counterparts - advocates of the purist Sunni Islam associated with Saudi Arabia - who today exhibit a small but influential presence among Europe's Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism may be compatible.
But an agreement requires giving and taking on both sides.
He questions the extent to which French political decision-makers (and the intellectual elite who so passionately guard the separation of church and state) really feel obliged to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may experience rougher treatment than Catholics, Protestants, and Jews, who in turn had to make their historic compromise with secular republicanism.
He rather recognizes a "tightening of the value screws" than a growing pragmatism.
Can Islam be French? After reading this book one is inclined to say "Yes, but not yet".
