enshrined in the country ’ s constitution in 1978, China ’ s One Child Policy is likely to be the most controversial order introduced by the ruling Communist Party to this day.
Couples who violate this policy must face enormous fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their jobs.
Chinese officials have attributed it to this policy that the critical use of natural resources could be avoided, while human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of policies.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who have already had a child to rub off.
Many couples also had sex selective abortions carried out, resulting in an unnaturally high relationship between men and women.
In recent years, government officials for populations have gradually weakened their stance on One Child Policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife were single children -- and in 2007, the tone of many harsh slogans was mitigated.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Beijing University Institute of Population Research, said that government officials have recently even discussed more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children with whom a partner is a single child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births in July.
Posters that taught families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines that describe in detail who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city administration has sent out municipal employees and volunteers for family planning to visit couples at home and to push through information sheets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial advice to those who have more than one child.
The reaction was not encouraging, said family planning officials.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the outskirts of Shanghai said that an upswing can be seen in the applications of couples who want a second child after the launch of the campaign, the urban districts do not report any change.
In the municipality of Huinan with a population of 115,000, only four to five applications are still received per month as an example.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the number of births expected in the city in 2010 will still be around 165,000 -- slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of the Shanghai community of Caolu, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to give their first the best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and that they would be legally permitted.
But, like many Chinese, they have only a small government health and life insurance.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West erroneously rate the One Child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child in the seventh month.
Yes, we are deprived of the opportunity to have more than one child.
