We do not want to make too many sacrifices.
UN Group drafts emission reduction plan
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been characterised by wild poses and mutual accusations -- has again focused on Friday with the publication of a document that records an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with industrial nations having to shoulder the greatest burdens in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a definitive political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, showed both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it has been seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that takes the time, with more than 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
The text, formulated by a specially created UN working group, is silent on the money supply that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can master global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how advanced and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions, and how high the upper limit of the global temperature increase that policymakers would support.
The process is given great flexibility, said John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed the six-page document, has summarised a 180 page negotiating text to focus on what the UN ’ s leading climate protection representative, Yvo de Boer, called “the big whole. ”
It shows the outline of a possible agreement whereby industrialised nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45% by 2020, compared to 1990 limits, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30% in the same period.
Together, countries could cut emissions by 50 to 95% by 2050.
The European Community has also given the talks on Friday a boost through its commitment to provide US $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change, from the master of floods and droughts to the prevention of deforestation.
Friday nevertheless brought the same verbal fireworks that had determined the talks last week.
The American climate mentor Todd Stern has rejected formulations calling for binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for developed countries, compared with voluntary reductions for major emerging economies, if they are not financed by developed nations.
This train announced that the Obama administration is heading a harder line with China than representatives of the Bush administration did not even two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without larger emerging economies getting up and taking action, said Stern, who also complained that the text was not going far enough to ensure that the cuts could be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern gave his opinion one hour after the statement by China ’ s Deputy Secretary of State He Yafei, which said that the leading American climate negotiator was either lacking “reason ” or“ most irresponsible ” of him, saying earlier this week that the United States would not help China financially to master global warming.
By jeopardising the future economic direction of the world ’ s major powers, fault lines have opened up both within industrialized nations and between industrialized nations and emerging economies.
The current struggle relates equally to the rescue of individual economies, as well as to the rescue of the planet, with China and the United States committing themselves to their obligations, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take more courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the major powers are fighting to see who should bear the cost of halting greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have moved to take more aggressive action to hold the countries with very high greenhouse gas levy accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game from which a new economic supremacy will develop, says Ulate, who also works as a regional climate change consultant for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the effects of climate change said they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although the leading participants say that the talks will at best lead to a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, with 43 members, tabled a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge's butcher, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the small island states' offensive 'exerts political pressure on the whole political process', partly because they are now united and demand measures from emerging countries, such as China and India.
The talks were given a new urgency when the delegates focused on the fact that most of the outstanding questions had to be resolved before the arrival of the leaders in order to reach an agreement.
High-level representatives, such as India ’ s Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and China ’ s Vice Minister, stepped out of their aircraft and raced through the corridors of the Bella Center for meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to mark out claims that will be negotiated next week.
The mere extent of the meeting -- 13,000 people go to the Congress Centre every day, and guitar-playing activists do nightly shows in which they make fun of the countries that they think betray and sell, and draft contracts are passed on from hand to hand rather than via e-mail -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just building up: almost all important ministers are here now and from Wednesday, 60 government leaders will be in Copenhagen.
We come to the Oberliga, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice President for Global Policy of the Organization Conservation International.
The heavy weights come.
