The cradle of dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: the two meter long and 1.50 meter tall animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body features, according to Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in today's New Mexico, which at that time was in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangäa at the equator.
Tawa opens a new window on the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the relationship, the propagation and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavation on the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaurs in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Triassic, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as new species.
During the excavation, they gathered the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories about Dino's early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi and Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary discovery: "Dinosaurs are extremely rare, mostly only single fragments."
Other dinosaurs do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current doctrine, dinosaurs appeared for the first time about 230 million years ago.
Many of the oldest fossils, however, are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these urine dinos is usually controversial.
For example, the experts are debating when the lizards split into their three main lines of development: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the four-legged sauropods and their relatives known as "long-legged necks", and the Ornithischia (bird-crested aurians), which included, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
After the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air bags, as they also possess the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of the birds is more efficient than that of the mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the giant Sauropods later also possessed airbags and lightweight bones, probably already the common ancestor of both groups had produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known so far lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards appeared there for the first time.
Thus, the three development lines separated early and spread from South America over all parts of the world, which at that time still formed a single land mass as a supercontinent Pangäa.
The fact that the team together with Tawa hallae found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods speaks for this.
The three cannot come from a common immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe that there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says the Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted picture, because in South America there have simply been a lot of primitive dinosaurs, while on other continents hardly anything can be found.
As the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare lateral line of the reptile stem to the dominant farmers of the Middle Ages, it is still mysterious.
During the Triassic the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the flying aurians and with numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the relationship died out on the border from the Triassic to the Jura.
Success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There might have been a mass death that the dinosaurs happened to survive, but not the other reptiles.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so that they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story did not last forever.
150 million years later a meteorite impact helped a group of animals to bloom, which had also developed in the Triassic and since then has been a shadow existence: the mammals.
