Discrimination in work has increased in recent years, especially among the younger women who want to have children.
This is the result of a study carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute for Women "The Fertility and Career of Women in Spain".
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities restricted on the labour market due to their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are large differences in the decision to establish a family and the number of children, depending on whether women work or not, and if so what kind of job they are doing.
Those of them who do no other work outside the house, work only half-day or have no fixed employment contract, are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with a firm job, especially in the public sphere, postpone the founding of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"Women in the age group between 35 and 49 years with a permanent employment receive their first child on average only 3.7 years after the contraction, a figure that increases to 4.1 years for women with fixed employment who have taken longer to achieve this and who have realized their contraction and the first child only much later.
In addition, the type of work has a great influence on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar in terms of willingness to conceive, "explains the CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, at the time of marriage and the first child, the higher the level of education.
This difference could also be found in women of the same age.
For example, women in the group aged between 35 and 49, depending on whether they have only primary or higher education, were on average their first mother at 25.1 or 32.1.
Furthermore, there is another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
Whereas the women who have graduated from primary school marry before their first permanent employment and receive their first child, the women with a middle or high school leaving certificate do it exactly differently and first seek a permanent employment and get married afterwards and then get their first child, notes Delgado.
