As in the case of the ABS anti-lock brake system and as in the case of ESP, the auxiliary systems for braking in emergencies must become a mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already obligatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, and for the remaining vehicles a period of grace has been set by the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure decided by the European Union is to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help prevent many rear-end accidents due to their operation.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical brake manoeuvre which the system recognizes on the brake pedal based on the brake strength carried out by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident were no longer able to step onto the brake pedal before the collision, and half of them had not slowed down with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake assistance, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the brake system and thus reduces the braking time and therefore also the braking distance that a car travels during the braking process.
According to a study by the EU, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assist.
There would be even fewer accidents - it is expected that one in four accidents could be prevented from personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system will help him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not react to the warning and even if the collision is inevitable, the brake assist exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes to keep the damage as low as possible.
